##

EXAMPLE: tests/modulo_and_remainder.stult

This example checks the difference between mathematical modulo and truncating
remainder.

MOD follows the divisor's sign, while REM follows the dividend's sign.

##

ASSERT : STD["ASSERT"]
MATH : STD["MATH"]

ASSERT["EQUAL"](
	MATH["MOD"](10, 3)
	MATH["REM"](10, 3)
	"MOD and REM should match for positive operands"
)

ASSERT["EQUAL"](
	MATH["MOD"](-10, 3)
	2
	"MOD should wrap a negative dividend into the positive divisor range"
)

ASSERT["EQUAL"](
	MATH["REM"](-10, 3)
	-1
	"REM should follow the sign of a negative dividend"
)

ASSERT["EQUAL"](
	MATH["MOD"](10, -3)
	-2
	"MOD should follow the sign of a negative divisor"
)

ASSERT["EQUAL"](
	MATH["REM"](10, -3)
	1
	"REM should follow the sign of a positive dividend"
)

ASSERT["EQUAL"](
	MATH["MOD"](-10, -3)
	MATH["REM"](-10, -3)
	"MOD and REM should match when both operands are negative"
)

ASSERT["EQUAL"](
	MATH["REM"](10.5, 3)
	1.5
	"REM should support decimal dividends"
)

ASSERT["EQUAL"](
	MATH["REM"](-10.5, 3)
	-1.5
	"REM should truncate decimal division toward zero"
)
